 <div xml:id="commentary" type="section">
 <head>Historical Commentary</head>
 <p>In the aftermath of the reforms of <name type="person" n="Cleisthenes"
 >Cleisthenes</name> of <date from="-0507" to="-0508">508/7
 BCE</date>, the new Athenian democracy sought to establish a presence in
 the <placeName key="Saronic Gulf">Saronic Gulf</placeName> against its
 <placeName key="Peloponnese">Peloponnesian</placeName> (led by <placeName
 key="Sparta">Sparta</placeName>) and <placeName key="Isthmus"
 >Isthmian</placeName> (led by <placeName key="Corinth">Corinth</placeName>)
 opponents. The nearby island of <placeName key="Aegina">Aegina</placeName> and
 the city-state of <placeName key="Corinth">Corinth</placeName> adjacent to the
 <placeName key="Isthmus">Isthmus</placeName> both had spheres of interest in
 the <placeName key="Saronic Gulf">Saronic Gulf</placeName>. These and other
 <foreign xml:lang="xgrc">
 <w n="po/leis">poleis</w>
 </foreign> were active members of the Peloponnesian League, which was led by
 <placeName key="Sparta">Sparta</placeName> and included <placeName
 key="Athens">Athens</placeName>. The island of <placeName key="Salamis"
 >Salamis</placeName>, which <placeName key="Athens">Athens</placeName> had
 seized in the age of <name type="person" n="Pisistratus">Pisistratus</name> the
 tyrant <date n="-560">ca. 560 BCE</date> (<bibl 
 type="cts-urn" n="urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0525.tlg001:1.3.3">Paus. 1.3.3</bibl>, <bibl 
 type="cts-urn" n="urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0525.tlg001:9.6.2">9.6.2</bibl>), provided the ideal base for such a presence. This,
 the earliest decree of the Athenian <foreign xml:lang="xgrc">
 <w n="dh=mos">dēmos</w>
 </foreign>, addresses the rights and responsibilities of <foreign xml:lang="xgrc">
 <w n="klhrou=xoi">kleruchoi</w>
 </foreign> or <soCalled>cleruchs</soCalled> (Athenian citizens dwelling outside
 of <placeName key="Athens">Athens</placeName> who retain their <term sortKey="citizenship">citizenship</term>) settled by <placeName key="Athens"
 >Athens</placeName> on the island: cleruchs must pay taxes and provide
 military services to <placeName key="Athens">Athens</placeName>, they may lease
 the land only to kinsmen (the text here is fragmentary and may refer instead to
 a dweller) on penalty of a fine, and they must provide their own weapons. The
 text also refers to an Athenian <term sortKey="archon">archon</term>
 [here, the local governor, as at <title>LSJ</title> s.v. <foreign xml:lang="grc"
 >a)/rxon</foreign>, II.2; cf. <bibl type="cts-urn" n="urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0086.tlg003:54.7-54.8">Aristot. <title>Ath. Pol.</title>
 54.7-8</bibl>]), whose responsibilities seem to focus on military assessment,
 and the boulē or <term sortKey="Council">Council</term> of 500
 (<bibl type="cts-urn" n="urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0525.tlg001:1.3.5">Paus. 1.3.5</bibl>)
 recently created by <name type="person">Cleisthenes</name>.</p>
 <p>Who are these settlers, and what does their relocation to <placeName
 key="Salamis">Salamis</placeName>
 <date from="-0510" to="-0500">ca. 510-500 BCE</date> tell us about the
 constitutional reforms of <name type="person">Cleisthenes</name>? The
 inscription has long been recognized as the first extant Athenian decree and so
 has undergone considerable scrutiny. Although the various provisions that detail
 the fiscal and military obligations of those settled on the island have received
 attention in the scholarship, surely the most controversial passage lies at the
 end of line 1, and it is here that the identity of the settlers was articulated
 in this no-longer extant portion of the decree. The new fragment published by
 Matthaiou confirms the accusative plural <foreign xml:lang="grc">-os</foreign>
 ending, but does not resolve whether the settlers were referred to as <foreign
 xml:lang="xgrc">
 <w xml:lang="xgrc" n="klhrou=xoi">clerouchs</w>
 </foreign> or as Athenian citizens.</p>
 <p><foreign xml:lang="xgrc">
 <w xml:lang="xgrc" n="klhrouxi/a">Cleruchies</w>
 </foreign> were a phenomenon mostly of <date from="-0499" to="-0400"
 >5th</date> and <date from="-0399" to="-0300">4th century</date>
 <placeName key="Athens">Athens</placeName>, and in simplest terms amounted to a
 community of Athenian colonists inhabiting territory outside of <placeName
 key="Attica">Attica</placeName> with all of the rights and obligations of
 Athenian citizens (Graham 1983, 167ff.; the scholiast to <bibl 
 type="cts-urn" n="urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0033.tlg002:2.19">Pindar 2.19</bibl> refers to <name
 type="person">Timodemos</name>, of the Attic deme of <name type="deme"
 n="Acharnai">Acharnai</name> but a clerouch on <placeName key="Salamis"
 >Salamis</placeName>). With the exception of the cleruchy at <placeName
 key="Chalcis">Chalcis</placeName> in the aftermath of the conflict with
 <placeName key="Athens">Athens</placeName> in 506 BCE (where <name
 type="ancientAuthor">Herodotus</name> refers to the settlement of 4000
 Athenians on the land of well-to-do Chalcidians: <bibl 
 type="cts-urn" n="urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0016.tlg001:5.77.2">Hdt. 5.77.2</bibl>, 6.100.1), and <placeName
 key="Salamis">Salamis</placeName>—if the restoration is
 correct—<placeName key="Athens">Athens</placeName> dispatched no
 other cleruchs until the middle of the 5th century (for a list of the cleruchies
 ca. 450 BCE, see <title>OCD</title> s.v. <soCalled>cleruchy</soCalled>). The
 restoration of <foreign xml:lang="grc"><add>klero/x</add>os</foreign> supports the
 interpretation that an Athenian cleruchy on <placeName key="Salamis"
 >Salamis</placeName> following on the heels of the <placeName key="Chalcidice"
 >Chalcidian</placeName> settlement would serve as a none-too-subtle
 challenge to the authority of the Peloponnesian League in the Saronic Gulf
 (Taylor 1997, 13-15, who with Luria suggests a date as early as 510-508 BCE).
 These cleruchs on <placeName key="Salamis">Salamis</placeName> will have joined
 other resident non-native citizens who held deme membership back in <placeName
 key="Attica">Attica</placeName> but lived on the island. Thus, <name
 type="person" n="Cleisthenes">Cleisthenes</name>’ political
 reorganization of <placeName key="Athens">Athens</placeName> and <placeName
 key="Attica">Attica</placeName> may well have included efforts to create
 nearby pockets of Athenian <term sortKey="citizens">citizens</term> who
 could promote <placeName key="Athens">Athens</placeName>’ political
 agenda, even on the doorstep of her allies and rivals in the <placeName
 key="Saronic Gulf">Saronic Gulf</placeName> and <placeName key="Chalcis"
 >Chalcis</placeName>. </p>
